		                    <div id="content" class="col col-8">


<article class="list content widget expert-content" itemprop="articleBody">
		<section class="list-unit group">
			<div class="expert-content-text"><p>One of the great aspects about <a href="/od/cocktailrecipes/tp/halloween_cktl.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="1">Halloween cocktails</a> is that you can have a lot of fun with the presentation. This is the occasion in which you can think of your <a href="/od/embellishments/Drink_Presentation.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="2">cocktail garnishes</a> just as you would your costume and there is virtually no limit to where your imagination can take you.</p><p>Below are a few simple suggestions to get you started in creating the creepiest of adornments for your drinks.</p></div>
		</section>


		<section class="list-unit group">
		<figure class="content-img content-img-small right-gutter">
			<div class="content-img-wrapper">
<img src="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/L/k/n/-/-/Lychee-Eyeball-Garnish.jpg" alt="Lychee Eyeball Garnish for Halloween Cocktails - Photo Courtesy: &copy; Shannon Graham" width="300" height="200" class="" data-pinit-img-url="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/k/n/-/-/Lychee-Eyeball-Garnish.jpg" data-description="11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Eyeballs" itemprop="image" >
			
<a href="http://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http://cocktails.about.com/od/embellishments/tp/Creepy-Cocktail-Garnishes.htm?utm_source=pinterest&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_campaign=shareurlbuttons_nip&media=http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/k/n/-/-/Lychee-Eyeball-Garnish.jpg&description=11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Eyeballs" data-component="contentListPage" data-source="pinitBtn" data-type="sharePinterest" data-ordinal="1" data-network="pinterest" title="Pin to Pinterest" class="pinit-btn" data-pin-do="skipLink"></a>			</div>
				<figcaption class="content-img-subtitle">
                    This eyeball garnish may look disgusting, but the mix of fruit is great and it's a perfect compliment to fruit martinis.
						<span class="credit">Photo Courtesy: &copy; Shannon Graham</span>
				</figcaption>
		</figure>
				<div class="expert-content-text">
					<h3 class="item-heading">
						
							1.&nbsp;
Eyeballs
					</h3>
	
							<p>The eyeball is a creepy organ and there is no time better than Halloween to bring them out. There are many ways to construct eyeballs to use for garnishes and which you choose is going to depend a lot on the style of drink you are serving.</p><p>One of my favorite eyeballs is in the picture and goes with the <a href="/od/vodkadrinkrecipes/r/mad_eye_martini.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="1">Mad Eye Martini</a>, though it can compliment any number of light flavored or fruity drinks. This one is made with a lychee, a <a href="/od/cocktailsbyflavor/a/Blueberry-Cocktail-Recipes.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="2">blueberry</a>, and fruit preserves, which create the veins. It is a great concept and the <a href="/od/liqueurscordials/p/lychee_liqueur.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="3">lychee</a> is the perfect candidate for the casing because of its texture and membrane-like feel. A detailed tutorial can be found here: <a href="/od/embellishments/ss/DIY-Lychee-Eyeball-Garnish-for-Halloween.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="4">DIY Lychee Eyeball Garnish</a>.</p><p>Another eyeball you might try for savory drinks involves a radish and an olive. The idea is part of this <a href="/od/vodkadrinkrecipes/r/vampire_juice.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="5">Vampire Juice</a> drink. Here is a detailed tutorial with a few (much needed) tips: <a href="/od/embellishments/fl/How-to-Make-a-Radish-Eyeball-Garnish.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="6">How to Make a Radish Eyeball</a>.</p><p>These eyeballs inspired another version that uses onion and olive, which you can see in this YouTube video: <a href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v&#61;hAJCanLPPo0" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="externalLink" data-ordinal="7">drEYE Martini</a>.</p><p>So the effect of your eyeball creations is not lost, don&#39;t drown them in the drink, but skewer the eyes and rest it on top of the glass. Another option is to use them as ice by adding them to a full tray of water and freezing overnight.
							</p>
				</div>
			</section>

<div id="adsense1" adsense-numlinks="2" adsense-displaylabel="true" class="adsense-slot adsense"></div>
		

		<section class="list-unit group">
		<figure class="content-img content-img-small right-gutter">
			<div class="content-img-wrapper">
<img src="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/L/Z/n/-/-/JackOLantern-Hennessy.jpg" alt="Hennessy Cognac Jack-O-Lantern Cocktail - Photo Courtesy: &copy; Shannon Graham" width="300" height="200" class="" data-pinit-img-url="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/Z/n/-/-/JackOLantern-Hennessy.jpg" data-description="11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Pumpkin Top" itemprop="image" >
			
<a href="http://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http://cocktails.about.com/od/embellishments/tp/Creepy-Cocktail-Garnishes.htm?utm_source=pinterest&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_campaign=shareurlbuttons_nip&media=http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/Z/n/-/-/JackOLantern-Hennessy.jpg&description=11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Pumpkin Top" data-component="contentListPage" data-source="pinitBtn" data-type="sharePinterest" data-ordinal="2" data-network="pinterest" title="Pin to Pinterest" class="pinit-btn" data-pin-do="skipLink"></a>			</div>
				<figcaption class="content-img-subtitle">
                    This Jack-O-Lantern mixes Cognac and orange juice, though the 'pumpkin' garnish is the real treat.
						<span class="credit">Photo Courtesy: &copy; Shannon Graham</span>
				</figcaption>
		</figure>
				<div class="expert-content-text">
					<h3 class="item-heading">
						
							2.&nbsp;
Pumpkin Top
					</h3>
	
							<p>This is a clever and easy garnish that can be used in a multitude of drinks, especially those with a concentration of <a href="/od/cocktailrecipes/a/orange_cocktails.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="1">orange juice</a>, like this <a href="/od/brandyrecipes/r/jack_olantern.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="2">Jack O&#39;Lantern Cocktail</a>. By having the orange colored drink as a base and serving a it in a short, round glass the full effect of the pumpkin can be achieved.</p><p>Constructing this garnish is simple: Cut an orange wheel and a small lime peel. Twist the lime and poke it into the middle of the orange. This faux pumpkin cap will float on your drink and adding a straw to one side of the orange makes the cocktail below easy to drink.
							</p>
				</div>
			</section>

		

		<section class="list-unit group">
		<figure class="content-img content-img-small right-gutter">
			<div class="content-img-wrapper">
<img src="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/L/_/n/-/-/JackOLantern-LobbyBar.jpg" alt="Lobby Bar Jack O'Lantern Cocktail - Photo Courtesy: &copy; Shannon Graham" width="300" height="200" class="" data-pinit-img-url="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/_/n/-/-/JackOLantern-LobbyBar.jpg" data-description="11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Carving" itemprop="image" >
			
<a href="http://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http://cocktails.about.com/od/embellishments/tp/Creepy-Cocktail-Garnishes.htm?utm_source=pinterest&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_campaign=shareurlbuttons_nip&media=http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/_/n/-/-/JackOLantern-LobbyBar.jpg&description=11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Carving" data-component="contentListPage" data-source="pinitBtn" data-type="sharePinterest" data-ordinal="3" data-network="pinterest" title="Pin to Pinterest" class="pinit-btn" data-pin-do="skipLink"></a>			</div>
				<figcaption class="content-img-subtitle">
                    Have fun carving your oranges for this Jack O'Lantern Cocktail (complete with Jack Daniels).
						<span class="credit">Photo Courtesy: &copy; Shannon Graham</span>
				</figcaption>
		</figure>
				<div class="expert-content-text">
					<h3 class="item-heading">
						
							3.&nbsp;
Carving
					</h3>
	
							<p>Take your <a href="http://homecooking.about.com/od/howtocookvegetables/a/pumpkincarving.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="1">pumpkin carving skills</a> to a smaller medium by carving your garnish. This is a neat little trick that can go with almost any cocktail and is pictured here in this <a href="/od/whiskeyrecipes/r/Jack-O-Lantern.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="2">Jack O&#39; Lantern</a> made with (of all things) Jack Daniel&#39;s .</p><p>All you need is a knife or channel knife, a little patience, and some fruit to practice with. The orange is a perfect candidate because of its color and thick skin. The trick is to carve out the orange peel, leaving a thin layer of the white pith visible. The second trick is to carefully peel the circle you cut from the fruit. Like I said, a little patience and practice and you have a great garnish.</p><p>Try this technique with other citrus fruit as well, or you can do the same with hot pepper garnishes, cutting through the entire skin. Another great addition to the orange face is to burn it as you would any burnt orange peel.
							</p>
				</div>
			</section>

<div id="adsense2" adsense-numlinks="2" adsense-displaylabel="true" class="adsense-slot adsense"></div>
		

		<section class="list-unit group">
		<figure class="content-img content-img-small right-gutter">
			<div class="content-img-wrapper">
<img src="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/L/R/n/-/-/Bayou-Slime-Cocktail.jpg" alt="Bayou Slime Cocktail - Photo Courtesy: &copy; Shannon Graham" width="300" height="200" class="" data-pinit-img-url="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/R/n/-/-/Bayou-Slime-Cocktail.jpg" data-description="11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Slime" itemprop="image" >
			
<a href="http://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http://cocktails.about.com/od/embellishments/tp/Creepy-Cocktail-Garnishes.htm?utm_source=pinterest&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_campaign=shareurlbuttons_nip&media=http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/R/n/-/-/Bayou-Slime-Cocktail.jpg&description=11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Slime" data-component="contentListPage" data-source="pinitBtn" data-type="sharePinterest" data-ordinal="4" data-network="pinterest" title="Pin to Pinterest" class="pinit-btn" data-pin-do="skipLink"></a>			</div>
				<figcaption class="content-img-subtitle">
                    The torn mint on top of this rum-filled Bayou Slime is the perfect finishing touch.
						<span class="credit">Photo Courtesy: &copy; Shannon Graham</span>
				</figcaption>
		</figure>
				<div class="expert-content-text">
					<h3 class="item-heading">
						
							4.&nbsp;
Slime
					</h3>
	
							<p>We&#39;re not really talking about &#34;slime&#34; here, but more of a swampy sludge look that can be added to your drinks. This technique works best with drinks that include <a href="/od/cocktailsbyflavor/a/Cocktails-With-Eggs.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="1">egg</a> like the <a href="/od/rumrecipes/r/bayou_slime.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="2">Bayou Slime</a> pictured because of the foam that is created when shaking and straining these drinks.</p><p>The thick, white film that floats atop egg drinks is the ideal palate and any complimentary herb (in this case, mint) can be torn and scattered on top to complete the garnish. If an appropriate addition to the drink, add grated nutmeg or <a href="/od/mixology/ig/Herbs-and-Spices-in-Mixology/Cinnamon-Herb-in-Cocktails.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="3">cinnamon</a> for the look of dirt as well.
							</p>
				</div>
			</section>

		

		<section class="list-unit group">
		<figure class="content-img content-img-small right-gutter">
			<div class="content-img-wrapper">
<img src="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/L/b/n/-/-/Vampire-Kiss-Cocktail.jpg" alt="Finladia Vodka's Vampire Kiss Martini - Photo Courtesy: &copy; Shannon Graham" width="300" height="200" class="" data-pinit-img-url="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/b/n/-/-/Vampire-Kiss-Cocktail.jpg" data-description="11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Colored Sugar Rim" itemprop="image" >
			
<a href="http://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http://cocktails.about.com/od/embellishments/tp/Creepy-Cocktail-Garnishes.htm?utm_source=pinterest&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_campaign=shareurlbuttons_nip&media=http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/b/n/-/-/Vampire-Kiss-Cocktail.jpg&description=11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Colored Sugar Rim" data-component="contentListPage" data-source="pinitBtn" data-type="sharePinterest" data-ordinal="5" data-network="pinterest" title="Pin to Pinterest" class="pinit-btn" data-pin-do="skipLink"></a>			</div>
				<figcaption class="content-img-subtitle">
                    Add a little sparkle to your Halloween with this Vampire Kiss Martini.
						<span class="credit">Photo Courtesy: &copy; Shannon Graham</span>
				</figcaption>
		</figure>
				<div class="expert-content-text">
					<h3 class="item-heading">
						
							5.&nbsp;
Colored Sugar Rim
					</h3>
	
							<p>Drinks that call for a <a href="/od/embellishments/ss/rm_glass.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="1">sugar rim</a>, or that could be enhanced with one, can be transformed into a slightly creepier version for Halloween. This can be created by simply using red or black sugar as the <a href="/od/vodkadrinkrecipes/r/vampire_kiss.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="2">Vampire Kiss Martini </a>demonstrates.</p><p>There are two options for colored sugar. You can usually find it in the baking section of the grocery store. It is typically used for decorating sweets but makes a colorful rimming option well. The alternative is to add just a few drops of food coloring to white sugar to make any color you want. For Halloween, I prefer the latter because the liquid turns the sugar into more of a gooey substance that sticks easily to the glass, though it does also clump more.</p><p>Also, try running the rim through grenadine for a red base before the sugar for a more dynamic effect.
							</p>
				</div>
			</section>

<div id="adsense3" adsense-numlinks="1" adsense-displaylabel="true" class="adsense-slot adsense"></div>
		

		<section class="list-unit group">
		<figure class="content-img content-img-small right-gutter">
			<div class="content-img-wrapper">
<img src="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/L/d/Q/-/-/SKYY-Vampires-Kiss.jpg" alt="SKYY Vodka's Vampire's Kiss Halloween Cocktail - Photo Courtesy: &copy; SKYY Vodka" width="300" height="396" class="" data-pinit-img-url="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/d/Q/-/-/SKYY-Vampires-Kiss.jpg" data-description="11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Dripping Blood" itemprop="image" >
			
<a href="http://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http://cocktails.about.com/od/embellishments/tp/Creepy-Cocktail-Garnishes.htm?utm_source=pinterest&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_campaign=shareurlbuttons_nip&media=http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/d/Q/-/-/SKYY-Vampires-Kiss.jpg&description=11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Dripping Blood" data-component="contentListPage" data-source="pinitBtn" data-type="sharePinterest" data-ordinal="6" data-network="pinterest" title="Pin to Pinterest" class="pinit-btn" data-pin-do="skipLink"></a>			</div>
				<figcaption class="content-img-subtitle">
                    Vampire's Kiss.
						<span class="credit">Photo Courtesy: &copy; SKYY Vodka</span>
				</figcaption>
		</figure>
				<div class="expert-content-text">
					<h3 class="item-heading">
						
							6.&nbsp;
Dripping Blood
					</h3>
	
							<p>We are going to use another <a href="/od/Flavored-Vodka-Cocktails/r/Vampires-Kiss-Cocktail-Recipe.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="1">Vampire&#39;s Kiss</a> cocktail to demonstrate another bloody effect.</p><p>Essentially, you are going to use a red or other dark syrupy liquid to drizzle over the finished drink to create the look of dripping blood. <a href="/od/makeyourownmixers/r/grenadine.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="2">Grenadine</a> and <a href="/od/cocktailsbyflavor/a/Raspberry-Cocktails.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="3">raspberry liqueurs</a> are perfect for creating this look and are thick enough to suspend in the drink a little longer.</p><p>You can also freeze a red syrup inside the glass to create a foggy, bloody scene like this <a href="/od/vodkadrinkrecipes/r/Midori-Melon-Eye-Tini.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="4">Melon Eye-tini</a> demonstrates.</p><p>The <a href="/od/cocktailrecipes/r/The-Wolf-Bite.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="5">Wolf Bite</a> shooter also uses grenadine, while other drinks like <a href="/od/Liqueur-Cocktail-Recipes/r/Paranormal-Activity-Licorice-Trick-Cocktail-Recipe.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="6">Paranormal Activity</a> and the <a href="/od/cocktailrecipes/r/ghostbuster_ckt.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="7">Ghostbuster</a> use other liqueurs to create ghostly floats.
							</p>
				</div>
			</section>

		

		<section class="list-unit group">
		<figure class="content-img content-img-small right-gutter">
			<div class="content-img-wrapper">
<img src="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/L/a/F/-/-/spiders_kiss.jpg" alt="Spider's Kiss Cocktail - Midori Melon Liqueur - Photo Courtesy: &copy; Midori Melon Liqueur" width="300" height="467" class="" data-pinit-img-url="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/a/F/-/-/spiders_kiss.jpg" data-description="11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Spider Webs" itemprop="image" >
			
<a href="http://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http://cocktails.about.com/od/embellishments/tp/Creepy-Cocktail-Garnishes.htm?utm_source=pinterest&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_campaign=shareurlbuttons_nip&media=http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/a/F/-/-/spiders_kiss.jpg&description=11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Spider Webs" data-component="contentListPage" data-source="pinitBtn" data-type="sharePinterest" data-ordinal="7" data-network="pinterest" title="Pin to Pinterest" class="pinit-btn" data-pin-do="skipLink"></a>			</div>
				<figcaption class="content-img-subtitle">
                    Spider's Kiss Cocktail.
						<span class="credit">Photo Courtesy: &copy; Midori Melon Liqueur</span>
				</figcaption>
		</figure>
				<div class="expert-content-text">
					<h3 class="item-heading">
						
							7.&nbsp;
Spider Webs
					</h3>
	
							<p>I will admit, this is probably the most difficult garnish to pull off depending on your approach, but if you can get the technique down, your drinks will be stellar. There are a few ways to create the look of spider webs inside a glass...</p><p>The more interesting and far trickier is demonstrated in the <a href="/od/vodkadrinkrecipes/r/spiders_kiss.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="1">Spider&#39;s Kiss</a> and involves drawing the web with chocolate syrup. The key here is to work fast and freeze the glass immediately to avoid too many runs in your syrup. Then again, dripping chocolate can be an interesting effect as well.</p><p>The other technique is seen in one of mixologist Victoria D&#39;Amato-Moran&#39;s other <a href="/od/liqueurscordials/p/midori_liqueur.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="2">Midori</a> cocktails. In the <a href="/od/cocktailrecipes/r/green_ghoul.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="3">Green Ghoul</a> she uses black licorice strips placed along the sides and these are held in place by a generous pile of ice cubes.</p><p>Now, one last option is to put the webbing on the outside of the glass using glass markers, which can be found at most craft stores. Pick up some cheap glasses to paint and have fun creating the webbing, even adding highlights like the glass pictured.
							</p>
				</div>
			</section>

		

		<section class="list-unit group">
		<figure class="content-img content-img-small right-gutter">
			<div class="content-img-wrapper">
<img src="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/L/Y/n/-/-/HalloweenHypnotist-Cocktail.jpg" alt="Halloween Hypnotist Cocktail - Photo Courtesy: &copy; Shannon Graham" width="300" height="200" class="" data-pinit-img-url="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/Y/n/-/-/HalloweenHypnotist-Cocktail.jpg" data-description="11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Illumination" itemprop="image" >
			
<a href="http://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http://cocktails.about.com/od/embellishments/tp/Creepy-Cocktail-Garnishes.htm?utm_source=pinterest&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_campaign=shareurlbuttons_nip&media=http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/Y/n/-/-/HalloweenHypnotist-Cocktail.jpg&description=11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Illumination" data-component="contentListPage" data-source="pinitBtn" data-type="sharePinterest" data-ordinal="8" data-network="pinterest" title="Pin to Pinterest" class="pinit-btn" data-pin-do="skipLink"></a>			</div>
				<figcaption class="content-img-subtitle">
                    This Halloween Hypnotist cocktail will light up your night.
						<span class="credit">Photo Courtesy: &copy; Shannon Graham</span>
				</figcaption>
		</figure>
				<div class="expert-content-text">
					<h3 class="item-heading">
						
							8.&nbsp;
Illumination
					</h3>
	
							<p>Here is another very simple, yet effective, &#34;garnish.&#34; Essentially, you&#39;re just adding a glow stick to your drinks like the <a href="/od/vodkadrinkrecipes/r/hlwen_hpnotist.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="1">Halloween Hpnotist </a>demonstrates. The dual advantage here is that you get a cool looking drink <em>and</em> a stir stick. An alternative to this is to wrap a glowing necklace or bracelet around the stem of a glass, securing it with glue on either end.</p><p>This cool effect does need some warning. The chemicals inside a glow stick are nasty (<a href="http://chemistry.about.com/od/howthingsworkfaqs/a/howlightsticks.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="2">read more here</a>) so be sure that the sticks you use are not leaking before placing them in a drink. The other point - and I would hope this would go without saying - is, please rinse the sticks before putting them in anyone&#39;s drinks... it&#39;s simple sanitation.
							</p>
				</div>
			</section>

		

		<section class="list-unit group">
		<figure class="content-img content-img-small right-gutter">
			<div class="content-img-wrapper">
<img src="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/L/K/f/-/-/MolecularMixology-157287304.jpg" alt="Use dry ice to create a fog effect around cocktails. - Juanmonino / E+ / Getty Images" width="300" height="200" class="" data-pinit-img-url="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/K/f/-/-/MolecularMixology-157287304.jpg" data-description="11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Fog" itemprop="image" >
			
<a href="http://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http://cocktails.about.com/od/embellishments/tp/Creepy-Cocktail-Garnishes.htm?utm_source=pinterest&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_campaign=shareurlbuttons_nip&media=http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/K/f/-/-/MolecularMixology-157287304.jpg&description=11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Fog" data-component="contentListPage" data-source="pinitBtn" data-type="sharePinterest" data-ordinal="9" data-network="pinterest" title="Pin to Pinterest" class="pinit-btn" data-pin-do="skipLink"></a>			</div>
				<figcaption class="content-img-subtitle">
                    Use dry ice to create a fog effect around cocktails.
						<span class="credit">Juanmonino / E+ / Getty Images</span>
				</figcaption>
		</figure>
				<div class="expert-content-text">
					<h3 class="item-heading">
						
							9.&nbsp;
Fog
					</h3>
	
							<p>Dry ice is an ideal way to add a foggy atmosphere to a party and is perfect for use on a drink table or display.</p><p>A classic way to incorporate dry ice is to use it under a punch bowl illuminated by black lights. There are also these great <a href="http://chemistry.about.com/od/dryiceprojects/ig/Dry-Ice-Projects/" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="1">dry ice ideas</a> from About.com Chemistry Expert, Anne Helmenstine. The <a href="http://chemistry.about.com/od/dryiceprojects/ig/Dry-Ice-Projects/Glowing-Dry-Ice-Drink.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="2">foggy drink</a> and <a href="http://chemistry.about.com/od/dryiceprojects/ig/Dry-Ice-Projects/Glowing-Bloody-Hand-in-Punch.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="3">punch bowl hands</a> are two of my favorites.</p><p>Though it may be a neat effect, not everyone (myself included) enjoys dry ice directly in their drink and it has been known to have dangerous side effects. This is primarily due to drinkers unknowingly consuming the ice, usually because they do not realize (or are too drunk to know) that it is too cold to consume. Use caution when serving dry ice.</p><p>A unique dry ice idea comes from Nick Tether&#39;s <a href="/od/vodkadrinkrecipes/r/La-Dame-Blase-The-Jaded-Lady-Cocktail-Recipe.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="4">La Dame Blasee</a> cocktail. He uses dry ice as an aromatic back to the <a href="/od/liqueurscordials/g/absinthe.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="5">absinthe</a> and <a href="/od/spirits/p/vdka_101b.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="6">vodka cocktail</a>. A similar foggy cup could be used to compliment almost any cocktail.
							</p>
				</div>
			</section>

		

		<section class="list-unit group">
		<figure class="content-img content-img-small right-gutter">
			<div class="content-img-wrapper">
<a href="/od/rumrecipes/r/Goblet-Of-Fire.htm" data-component="contentListPage" data-source="outbound_list" data-type="link.articleReview" data-ordinal="1" source="outbound_list"></a><img src="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/L/W/Z/-/-/GobletFire-144444559.jpg" alt="Goblet of Fire - Visage / Stockbyte / Getty Images" width="300" height="200" class="" data-pinit-img-url="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/W/Z/-/-/GobletFire-144444559.jpg" data-description="11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Fire" itemprop="image" >
			
<a href="http://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http://cocktails.about.com/od/embellishments/tp/Creepy-Cocktail-Garnishes.htm?utm_source=pinterest&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_campaign=shareurlbuttons_nip&media=http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/W/Z/-/-/GobletFire-144444559.jpg&description=11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Fire" data-component="contentListPage" data-source="pinitBtn" data-type="sharePinterest" data-ordinal="10" data-network="pinterest" title="Pin to Pinterest" class="pinit-btn" data-pin-do="skipLink"></a>			</div>
				<figcaption class="content-img-subtitle">
                    Goblet of Fire.
						<span class="credit">Visage / Stockbyte / Getty Images</span>
				</figcaption>
		</figure>
				<div class="expert-content-text">
					<h3 class="item-heading">
						
<a href="/od/rumrecipes/r/Goblet-Of-Fire.htm" data-component="contentListPage" data-source="outbound_list" data-type="link.articleReview" data-ordinal="2">								10.&nbsp;
Fire
</a>					</h3>
	
							<p>The disclaimer first: Do not play with fire if you have been drinking. Also, be very careful anytime you light a drink on fire and be aware of surroundings, people, and other flammables nearby.</p><p>&#34;Parental&#34; warnings aside, fire is cool and drinks on fire are also cool. There&#39;s no dispute in that. You could try this <a href="/od/rumrecipes/r/Goblet-Of-Fire.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="1">Goblet of Fire</a>, a classic <a href="/od/whiskeyrecipes/r/blazer_cocktail.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="2">Blue Blazer</a>, a <a href="http://coffeetea.about.com/od/coffeeteacocktails/ss/Flaming-Spanish-Coffee-Recipe.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="3">Flaming Spanish Coffee</a>, or (for the more daring) a <a href="/od/rumrecipes/r/flame_drpepper.htm" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="4">Flaming Dr. Pepper</a> to add a little spark to your party.
								<a href="/od/rumrecipes/r/Goblet-Of-Fire.htm" data-component="contentListPage" data-source="outbound_list" data-type="link.articelReview" data-ordinal="1">More &raquo;</a>
							</p>
				</div>
			</section>

		

		<section class="list-unit group">
		<figure class="content-img content-img-small right-gutter">
			<div class="content-img-wrapper">
<img src="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/L/r/J/-/-/halloween-ice-tray.jpg" alt="Halloween Ice Cube Trays - Photo Courtesy: &copy; PriceGrabber.com" width="300" height="300" class="" data-pinit-img-url="http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/S/r/J/-/-/halloween-ice-tray.jpg" data-description="11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Ice" itemprop="image" >
			
<a href="http://pinterest.com/pin/create/button/?url=http://cocktails.about.com/od/embellishments/tp/Creepy-Cocktail-Garnishes.htm?utm_source=pinterest&amp;utm_medium=social&amp;utm_campaign=shareurlbuttons_nip&media=http://f.tqn.com/y/cocktails/1/0/r/J/-/-/halloween-ice-tray.jpg&description=11 Creepy Cocktail Garnishes for Halloween: Ice" data-component="contentListPage" data-source="pinitBtn" data-type="sharePinterest" data-ordinal="11" data-network="pinterest" title="Pin to Pinterest" class="pinit-btn" data-pin-do="skipLink"></a>			</div>
				<figcaption class="content-img-subtitle">
                    Halloween Ice Cube Trays.
						<span class="credit">Photo Courtesy: &copy; PriceGrabber.com</span>
				</figcaption>
		</figure>
				<div class="expert-content-text">
					<h3 class="item-heading">
						
							11.&nbsp;
Ice
					</h3>
	
							<p>Ice is essential in cocktails and if your Halloween drink menu includes those that are served over ice, you may want to use some ghoulish ice. One can find ice molds and trays in a variety of shapes, from skeletons and ghosts to fangs and pumpkins. It&#39;s a fun little addition to the party.</p><p><a href="http://erclk.about.com/?zi&#61;7/3X0j" rel="nofollow" data-component="link" data-source="inlineLink" data-type="internalLink" data-ordinal="1"><img src="http://0.tqn.com/w/bt/bc.gif" alt="Compare Prices" class="ilCp"/></a></p><p>You can also add fruit to ordinary cubes to add the illusion of mysterious floaters.</p><p>Those that I would avoid are the reusable ice cubes. They may be fun, but the ice in our cocktails is not there for the sole purpose of keeping the drink cool. The ice&#39;s adds to the drink, mellowing it over time and that is something that plastic ice cannot do.
							</p>
				</div>
			</section>

		
	



</article>


